metadata.name: I am rubber, you are glue #33
metadata.description:
The purpose of the artwork is to capture the gaze and stimulate the mind with it's synergy of geometric shapes and dynamic flows. I will try to lead you into an unexplored world where ellipses and rectangles form a vibrant grid, while a continuous flow of particles dances harmoniously within this abstract structure. The addition of a distinctive element, which I find fascinating, is the macram√®, providing a sense of connection between organic nature and the "digital nature."

The simple animation and interaction with the WASD keys were created to give a sense of constant movement and change without disrupting the canvas.

The use of color is carefully studied, with a subdued yet sophisticated palette, featuring delicate tones. This helps to keep the focus on the shapes and movement without excessive distractions.

Overall, the artwork aims to represent an example of how generative art can explore new aesthetic and narrative dimensions.

The functional keys are W, A, S, D, with a random tone. Press W to increase speed, press S to clear the frame.

To change the density from 1 to 8 (incorrect results set to 1), double-click the left mouse button.

I used p5.min.js - p5.sound.js.

P.S. The title comes from the witty and humorous dialogue typical of a famous 80s point-and-click video game:
"I am rubber, you are glue. A quote from my favorite macram√® artist."
It is a playful version of the well-known children's saying "I am rubber, you are glue, whatever you say bounces off me and sticks to you," but with a quirky twist involving macram√®.

metadata.name: Leaf study #40
metadata.description:
This piece is an exploration of the mathematical rules that dictate plant growth as well as their photosynthesis. 

Features : 
- 22 color palettes 
- 3 types of leaf  : oak, reniform, thistle
- 2 cell states : filled, hollow
- 2 color modes : light, dark

Controls
- Press S : export the piece 
- Press 1 - 9 : change the pixel density ( to increase the size of the export ). the default value is 2. Beware hight resolution will slow down the piece

metadata.name: Perforations #8
metadata.description:
Perforations is part of the Vertical Crypto Art Residency 6th Cohort Auction, 2023

++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Perforations is an exploration of time. 

What if we found a set of ancient artefacts buried underground for unknown millennia? What are they? Who made them? What are they trying to tell us? 

These artefacts have been somehow pierced, leaving behind holes in distinctive but unknown patterns. Their surfaces have been marked by the passage of time. Maybe the patterns are a message. Or a map. Or a clue. 

Perforations explores the idea of communicating across vast time scales, where there is no common language between those who left the artefacts and those who found them. 

The work invites us to imagine what information could have been so important that it needed to be recorded in this manner and left for future generations to discover. 

++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Press [p] = save an image (png) 
Press [v] = save a svg file

++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Created with svg.js, wtc-math, d3-delaunay

metadata.name: Face Hotel #14
metadata.description:
Face hotel is a digital and artistic version of the insect hotels we see while walking in parks.
This project is the result of a 4-hands work by visual artist Guillaumit and coder and musician Morusque.
For many years Guillaumit has been developing a work based on geometrical shapes combined in a personal way with delicate illustrative elements that seem to give his compositions a soul.
After having designed giant art projects in public spaces for collaborative frescoes Guillaumit decided to work in the world of generative art with the same concern of sincerity and singularity.
This canvas is fully generative and doesn't use predefined graphical assets. It has been designed to be viewed in 800x800, press ENTER to save a screenshot or ALT to save a 5x bigger picture.

metadata.name: Ecce Gratum #50
metadata.description:
"Ecce Gratum" is a symphony of colors and lines, a visual work that sings to the soul. The strokes of the brush are bold and confident, yet gentle and loving, like the notes of a symphony. The title, "Ecce Gratum", translates to "Behold the pleasing", and as you gaze upon this art, it is impossible not to be moved by its beauty and wonder. This painting is a celebration of life, a reminder to embrace the present and to find joy in the simple things. It is a call to look beyond the surface, to see the beauty in the world around us, and to let our hearts sing

[S] on live view to save a png

metadata.name: Sansuhwa #7
metadata.description: Once upon a time, in a house in an oriental village, you can see beautiful nature when you look at the window. This painting of nature is called "Sansuhwa." You can see the sun or the moon, the mountains, the sea, and the forest, but sometimes you can only see a part of them. And what you see in the bottom right is the way that Asian painting usually signs paintings. Usually, it is written in Chinese characters, but I made it specially in Korean.

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of Fran√ßois Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl

metadata.name: Sliders #23
metadata.description:
'Sliders' combines several geometric forms (including a '3D' representation of the cylinder) with a bright 'popping' color palette to create bold, abstract, geometric designs.

Creation: A series of colorfully illustrated layers (containing transparent regions) are stacked. Each layer is selected at random from several options. This means that each output is a unique artwork.

To download a 3150x3150px PNG:
Click/tap 'open', then click/tap the image to make a "Download image" button appear.

metadata.name: Lookouts #74
metadata.description:
Lookouts is a generative illustration done 100% in code using p5js. Inspired by my love for travel and minimalist design, this collection is built based on custom shapes filled with solid colors & limited texture.

The accompanying fxtext article (in ‚ÄòMentions‚Äô below) shares more details about the inspiration and development process of this project.

Lookouts renders as a fixed resolution output (2000 x 1666px). Controls (in live view): 
Press [4] to render at 4000 x 3333px
Press [8] to render at 8000 x 6666px
Press [s] to save the current view (default or higher resolution image)

metadata.name: StairWaves #171
metadata.description:
StairWaves is a generative collection imagining abstract stairs built in a wavy nature, with shadows being a key theme. While some waves are quite turbulent, others are just flat.

All shapes in the artwork are built using the same core logic applied in different ways. The method used to draw the waves is also used to draw the shadows, as well as the subtle textures on the surface of the waves. This homogeneous approach ensures a consistent and flowy feel to the final output.

StairWaves is coded entirely in p5.js. 

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)
